“Are you high?” just about
sums up the level of argument on
the question of legalizing mari-
juana for medicinal purposes.
Meanwhile, back at the ranch,
people make their own choices
regardless of the doctors and
lawyers. In my view, marijuana
should not be illegal because the
application of law to a user caus-
es more harm than the drug does,
not to mention that it’s a waste of
public money. But I’m not going
to rehash (pun intended) all the
arguments here; everyone can
ﬁnd reasons to support their own
beliefs. Instead, this column will
present a brief review of current
facts. which are known, or not
known, about this drug.

Marijuana, as a matter of
fact, is not a drug. According to
my sources, the word “marijua-
na” refers solely to the plant
material which contains over
400 different materials. Of these
materials, delta-9-tetrahydro-
carmabinol (THC) is a major
psychoactive chemical. THC is
absorbed quickly into virtually
every bodily tissue. Research has
shown that THC alters almost -all
biological systems in which it
has been examined, having a
“non-speciﬁc, ﬂuidizing effect
on membranes” —— yes mem-
branes, not memory, although
perhaps there is a connection
there. Research has shown that
THC has both contradictory and
inconsistent effects — for exam-
ple, both exciting and inhibiting
the release of various neurotrans-
mitters, and having sedative
effects without producing anes-
thesia. In addition to the “hard
science” (chemistry, physics) of

 

THC, “soft science” (psycholo-
gy, sociology) shows that the
effects of THC as reported by
users indicate that the cultural
milieu in which the drug is
ingested changes the reported
effects. - For example, North
American users commonly
report appetite stimulation; in
fact, this is one of the key rea-
sons of the “For Medical Use”
argument. Conversely, in
Jamaica, users report appetite
suppression.

Recognizing such cultural
differences is important to
putting THC in the right perspec-
tive; however, North American
research over the past several
years has yielded the following
gems: dose dependent impair-
ment of functions such as attend-
ing, speaking, problem solving,
and concept formation. This
means that a roomful of stoners
is likely to be a room full of peo-
ple all talking at cross purposes,
hardly able to remember what
the points of their sentences are
from begimiing to end, and mak-
ing profound connections they
are incapable of communicating
to one another. Well, it seemed
like fun at the time.

Apparently, it is only the
human race who enjoys the
effects of THC. It is universally
disliked by non-humans.
Neuroscientists refer to “tran-
sient cognitive and memory ‘dis-
ruptions.” This means, it feels
like somebody cut off the top of
your head, and your thoughts
rush out to mingle with the
world, while the world rushes in
to mingle with your thoughts.
Animals, sensible creatures, ﬁnd
this distracts them too much
from such important topics as “I

Pundit goes up in a puff of smoke

must ‘protect myself from preda-
tors.” Humans seem to like for-
getting about predators for a
while if they are in a position to
control their enviromnent, we
might conclude.

Despite such precautions as
a controlled environment, the
concentration of THC in any
given batch of marijuana varies
greatly. Acute panic reaction can
set in when dose is unusually
high. This is not usually fatal,
although it can be very scary at
the time and very embarrassing
afterwards. Far more ominous in
a long-terrn sense is the knowl-
edge that THC quite deﬁnitely
messes with memory storage and
retrieval. Nobody knows much
about this yet, but everyone
knows Alzheimers isn’t pretty.
Everybody also knows smoke is
not good for your lungs.

So, if you are high, just
remember, there’s no smoke
without ﬁre, and animals are
more sensible than humans. But,
such is life. If the effects of THC
are inconsistent and contradicto-

ry, well, maybe that’s why we '

like it: it’s just like us. I hope I
never need my doctor to pre-

scribe me marijuana to ease the

pain of some dreadful disease
and its worse treatment, but it
would be nice to know I could if
I had to. But either way, if I want
it, I’ll get it. There is no evidence
to suggest that THC interferes
with such qualities as ingenuity,
resourcefulness, and determina-
tion. Then again, I don’t think
anybody has looked into those
yet.

