Senior attacker Marc Polecritti
netted three goals and an assist to
lead the Pitt lacrosse team to an
11-2 blowout of St. Vincent
College on Saturday night.

The Panthers raised their
record to 1-0 with their win at St.

Vincent in front of more than 200

faithful Pitt fans.

“Overall, I was very pleased
with our play,” Head Coach Gary
Neft said. “For the first game of
the season, we played pretty well,
but we still have some things to
work on.”

Senior goaltender Dave Travis
and the Pitt defense was tough,
allowing only two goals, the sec-
ond coming late in the fourth quar-
ter. “Our defense was tremen-
dous,” Neft said. “They gave up
few shots and even fewer quality
shots.”

The game began with a few
scary minutes for-Pitt, when John
Gelsizer left the game early with
his second concussion in a week.
However, moments later, Polecritti
got the Panthers off to a fast start
for Pitt, scoring on a quick stick,
which is comparable to a one-timer
in hockey.

“[Po1ecritti’s] hat trick was
big,” co-captain Pat Shea said. “He
came in and scored a quick goal
that gave us a lift.”

The Panthers had five different
players scoring in the win with
Polecritti leading the way.

 

Panther lacrosse getting off
to a fast start with first win

Polecritti’s linemate, sophomore
attacker Matt Hoplamazain, also
netted a hat trick, and senior co-

captains Pat Shea and Rob Heapes 0

added offense and leadership. Shea
scored two goals, and Heapes
added one. Even freshman Dave
Corrado got in the mood, scoring
two goals and four assists.

“I’m very happy with the way I
played,” Polecritti said. “This is
the first time our line has played
together, and I’m very happy with
the way we are playing. This is an
excellent start to the season. We
just have to continue to step it up
and not get too cocky.”

The Panthers have a week to
enjoy their win until they play host
to Ohio University on Saturday,
Feb. 8, at 8:00 p.m. at the Cost
Center. ’ ‘

Ohio University is a first-year
team, but they could give the
Panthers some problems. Neft said
that their players are very experi-
enced and have played together
prior to forming a team. '

“We have some things to work
on before this week’s game with
Ohio University,” coach Neft said.
“This is our first league game and
it is a big game. This game will be
tougher than this past one with St.
Vincent.”

“We’re looking forward to
Ohio University,” Shea said. “That
is a big game. We were kind of
rusty, but we played pretty well.
We’re especially grateful for the
fans. We had great fan support this
past Saturday.” .

